## 1. What FSDP2 Is and Why It Matters for Accelerate

FSDP2 is PyTorch's current fully sharded data parallel implementation, exposed through
`torch.distributed.fsdp.fully_shard`. It replaces the class-based `FullyShardedDataParallel`
(now called FSDP1, which is officially deprecated as of PyTorch 2.x).

The fundamental difference: FSDP1 concatenates all parameters of a wrapped module into a
single flat 1D tensor (`FlatParameter`) and shards that. FSDP2 shards each parameter
individually as a `DTensor` (Distributed Tensor) split on `dim=0`. The implications flow
through the entire stack: state dicts, mixed precision, optimizer interaction, LoRA/PEFT
compatibility, and memory management all behave differently.

For Accelerate as a library, FSDP2 matters because:

- The HuggingFace ecosystem (Transformers `Trainer`, TRL, PEFT) runs on top of Accelerate. FSDP2 unblocks correct QLoRA fine-tuning, FP8 all-gather, and per-layer mixed precision without workarounds.
- PyTorch's own recommendation is to migrate everything to FSDP2. FSDP1 will not receive new features.
- Accelerate's FSDP2 integration (added in ~v0.34) is newer and has known gaps compared to the mature FSDP1 path. This is where contributor leverage is highest.

