## 5. Model Initialization Patterns

### Pattern 1: Standard (Model Already in GPU Memory)

Use when the model fits in CPU RAM on at least one machine before sharding.

```python
from accelerate import Accelerator
from accelerate.utils import FullyShardedDataParallelPlugin
from transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM

plugin = FullyShardedDataParallelPlugin(fsdp_version=2, reshard_after_forward=True)
accelerator = Accelerator(fsdp_plugin=plugin)

# Load on rank 0 only, other ranks get meta tensors
with accelerator.main_process_first():
    model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(
        "meta-llama/Llama-3-8B",
        low_cpu_mem_usage=True,
    )

optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-4)

# CRITICAL: pass model and optimizer together
model, optimizer, dataloader = accelerator.prepare(model, optimizer, dataloader)
```

### Pattern 2: Meta Device Initialization (Recommended for 70B+ models)

Never instantiates the full model in CPU RAM. Parameters are on meta device (no actual
memory) until FSDP2 shards and materializes them on-device.

```python
from torch.nn import init as nn_init
from accelerate import init_empty_weights

# Create model structure on meta device: zero memory allocated
with init_empty_weights():
    model = MyTransformer(config)

# prepare() calls fully_shard which moves meta tensors to GPU shards
# then calls model.to_empty(device="cuda") + model.reset_parameters()
# to materialize the shards with real (random) values
optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-4)
model, optimizer = accelerator.prepare(model, optimizer)

# Load pre-trained weights after sharding:
accelerator.load_state("./pretrained_checkpoint/")
```

### Pattern 3: PyTorch-Native fully_shard (No Accelerate Wrapping)

Useful for benchmarking or when you need direct control over every FSDP2 detail.

```python
import torch
import torch.distributed as dist
from torch.distributed.fsdp import fully_shard, FSDPModule, MixedPrecisionPolicy
from torch.distributed.device_mesh import init_device_mesh

dist.init_process_group(backend="nccl")
device = torch.device(f"cuda:{dist.get_rank()}")
torch.cuda.set_device(device)

mesh = init_device_mesh("cuda", (dist.get_world_size(),))

mp_policy = MixedPrecisionPolicy(
    param_dtype=torch.bfloat16,
    reduce_dtype=torch.float32,
)

# Bottom-up: sub-modules first
model = MyTransformer(config).to(device)
for layer in model.layers:
    fully_shard(layer, mesh=mesh, mp_policy=mp_policy, reshard_after_forward=True)
fully_shard(model, mesh=mesh, mp_policy=mp_policy, reshard_after_forward=True)

# Verify sharding
for name, param in model.named_parameters():
    assert isinstance(param, DTensor), f"{name} is not sharded"
    assert param.placements == (Shard(0),)
    print(f"{name}: local shape {param.to_local().shape}")

# Optimizer after sharding
optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-4)
```

### Verifying the Type Union

After `fully_shard`, inspect what the model became:

```python
from torch.distributed.fsdp import FSDPModule

print(type(model))
# <class 'FSDPMyTransformer'>  -- joint class

print(isinstance(model, MyTransformer))   # True
print(isinstance(model, FSDPModule))      # True

# FSDPModule-specific methods are now available:
model.unshard()    # manually trigger all-gather
model.reshard()    # manually free unsharded copy
```

