## 11. CPU Offload

CPU offload stores parameter shards in CPU RAM when they are not being actively computed.
Parameters are moved to GPU only during the all-gather window, then moved back.

### When to Use

Use when the model barely fits on GPU with FSDP sharding alone, and you have enough CPU RAM.
The penalty is PCIe bandwidth latency on every all-gather (parameters travel CPU->GPU).
On NVLink servers this penalty is severe; on PCIe servers it depends on model size vs batch size.

### Configuration

```python
from torch.distributed.fsdp import CPUOffloadPolicy

plugin = FullyShardedDataParallelPlugin(
    fsdp_version=2,
    cpu_offload=CPUOffloadPolicy(
        offload_params=True,
        pin_memory=True,   # pinned memory enables DMA, faster transfer
    ),
)
```

YAML:

```yaml
fsdp_config:
  fsdp_version: 2
  fsdp_offload_params: true
```

### Memory Profile with Offload

```
Without offload, FULL_SHARD on 4 GPUs:
  GPU memory = (model_bytes / 4) + largest_unit_working_set + activations

With offload, FULL_SHARD on 4 GPUs:
  GPU memory = largest_unit_working_set + activations
  CPU memory = model_bytes / 4   (each rank's shard)
```

Offload can reduce GPU memory by the full shard footprint, but step time increases because
every all-gather involves a CPU->GPU copy. With `pin_memory=True` the copy is asynchronous
and can partially overlap with the compute of earlier layers.

