## 18. Quick Diagnostic Checklist

Use this when something breaks with FSDP2. Work top to bottom.

```
[ ] Is fsdp_version: 2 set in the config?
    -> If not, you're running FSDP1. Check fsdp_version field.

[ ] Are model and optimizer passed together to prepare()?
    -> FSDP2 requires both in the same call. Separate calls raise ValueError.

[ ] Is the optimizer created AFTER prepare() or at least passed with the model?
    -> Optimizer must see DTensor parameters, not original torch.Tensors.

[ ] Is model(x) used instead of model.forward(x)?
    -> model.forward() bypasses pre-forward hooks and skips the all-gather.
       Always call model(x).

[ ] Are fully_shard calls applied bottom-up?
    -> Sub-modules first, root last. If root is sharded first, sub-module
       sharding is ignored.

[ ] Is the checkpoint loading correct?
    -> SHARDED_STATE_DICT checkpoints must be loaded with dcp.load(),
       not torch.load(). Use accelerator.load_state() for the safe path.

[ ] Are there NaN/Inf gradients?
    -> Check reduce_dtype. With reduce_dtype=bfloat16 at large batch sizes,
       gradient precision loss can cause instability. Switch to reduce_dtype=float32.

[ ] Does memory spike unexpectedly?
    -> Profile with torch.cuda.memory_stats(). Memory spikes during forward
       suggest reshard_after_forward=False (SHARD_GRAD_OP). Switch to True.
    -> Spikes during save suggest FULL_STATE_DICT. Switch to SHARDED_STATE_DICT.

[ ] Does FSDP2 with activation checkpointing produce wrong gradients?
    -> Suspected bug. See G1 in §15. Temporarily disable activation checkpointing
       and confirm gradients are correct. File an issue if confirmed.

[ ] LoRA/PEFT adapter weights are not updating?
    -> Check if adapter parameters are being treated as ignored. See G3 in §15.
       Workaround: manually call fully_shard on adapter layers with reshard_after_forward=False
       so they participate in communication but with minimal overhead.
```
